revision.text:
{{distinguish|text=the [[1984 Kokkilai massacre (LTTE)]]}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}} {{Infobox civilian attack | title = Kokkilai massacre | image = | caption = | map = Location map Sri Lanka Northern Province EN.svg | map_caption = Location of [[Northern Province, Sri Lanka]] | location = [[Mullaitivu District]], [[Northern Province, Sri Lanka|Northern Province]], [[Sri Lanka]] | coordinates = | target = [[Sri Lankan Tamil]] Civilians | date = 15–16 December 1984 | time = | timezone = +8 GMT | type = | fatalities = 131 | injuries = Unknown | perps = [[Sri Lankan military]] | susperps = | weapons = }}
'''1984 Kokkilai massacres''' refers to a series of massacres of [[Sri Lankan Tamil people|Sri Lankan Tamil]] civilians when the [[Sri Lankan military]] attacked the village of [[Kokkilai]] and several neighboring villages in [[Mullaitivu District]], [[Northern Province, Sri Lanka]]. The attack left several civilians including women and children dead and their property destroyed. The attacks resulted in widespread displacement of native residents and subsequently their lands were [[Sri Lankan state sponsored colonisation schemes|colonized]] by [[Sinhalese people|Sinhala]] settlers.<ref name="NESHOR">{{cite book | last = | first = | authorlink = NESHOR | title = Massacres of Tamils(1956-2008) | publisher = Manitham Publications | series = | volume = | edition = | location = Chennai | year = 2009 | page = 15 | doi = | isbn = 978-81-909737-0-0 | mr = | zbl = }}</ref>
==Incident== On 15 December 1984, a large number of [[Sri Lankan military]] troops entered the coastal villages of [[Kokkilai]], [[Kokkuthoduvai]], [[Alampil]], [[Nayaru]] and [[Kumulamunai]] in [[Mullaitivu District]]. The Sri Lankan Army arrived and announced that several villages were to vacate within 24 hours. Entire villages in the region such as Kokkilai, Kokkuthuduvai, Karnaddu kerni and Koddai Keri amongst others were ordered to vacate within a day’s time. The military then began killing people and destroying property. 131 civilians were killed including 31 women and 21 children. More than 2,000 families were forced to relocate following the attacks and subsequent colonisation attempts of their lands by the Sinhala population. They remain displaced to this date.<ref name="NESHOR"/><ref name="pts">{{cite web | url=http://www.ptsrilanka.org/images/documents/state_aided_sinhala_colonisation_en.pdf | title=State aided Sinhala colonisation | publisher=PTS Sri Lanka | accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref>
==State colonization of Tamil areas== The Kokkilai massacres has come to be viewed as a part of the greater Sri Lankan state sponsored colonization of Sinhalese in Tamil areas.<ref name="jds">{{cite web | url=http://www.jdslanka.org/index.php/news-features/politics-a-current-affairs/181-systematic-sinhalisation-of-fishing-livelihood-in-jaffna-mullaitivu-tamil-politicians | title='Systematic Sinhalisation in North' - Tamil politicians | publisher=JDS Lanka | accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref>
The [[Mullaitivu District]] had historically been a Tamil area, and the population was almost entirely Tamil in the district. The villages situated at the southernmost part of the district, serving as the vital link between the [[Northern Province, Sri Lanka|North]] and the [[Eastern Province, Sri Lanka|East]] became favorite targets for colonies of the Government. The fishing villages in the district including [[Kokkilai]] were colonized by Sinhala fishermen from [[Negombo]] and [[Chilaw]].<ref name="Sangam">{{cite web|url=http://www.sangam.org/articles/view2/?uid=633|title=Chapter 23: Manal Aru becomes Weli Oya|last=T. Sabaratnam|work=Pirapaharan|publisher=Ilankai Tamil Sangam|accessdate=4 October 2009}}</ref>
In December 1984, the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] reprised these colonization attempts by attacking these newly established colonies in North-East which were heavily protected by [[Sri Lankan military]] and Sri Lankan Home Guards who had earlier [[ethnic cleansing|ethnically cleansed]] the native Tamil population from these villages.
Following the recapture of the North and East by Government forces, the land border between [[Mullaitivu District]] and [[Trincomalee District]] were once again colonized with Sinhalese settlers in what were traditionally Tamil lands. Sinhalese were settled in traditionally Tamil land, given land, money to build homes and security provided by the [[Special Task Force]].<ref>[http://www.uthr.org/Reports/Report8/chapter1.htm The war - one year on]</ref> As a result, the demographics of the region had been significantly altered and a new division called the [[Weli Oya Divisional Secretariat]] (a Sinhalese corruption of the Tamil term ""Manal Aru") was carved in the southern parts of the Mullaitivu district. Today the majority of the population in the area is Sinhalese while Tamils have been systematically denied any claim to their lands.<ref>''Sensitive colonization in Manal Aru area in Mullaithivu district.'' [http://www.uthr.org/Reports/Report8/chapter1.htm UTHR]</ref>
==See also== * [[Sri Lankan state sponsored colonisation schemes]] * [[1984 Manal Aru massacres]]
