{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}
The '''Battle of Barking Creek''' was a [[friendly fire]] incident over England on 6 September 1939, resulting in the first death of a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[fighter pilot]] in the [[World War II|Second World War]].

==Battle==

[[File:Royal Air Force Fighter Command, 1939-1945. CH162.jpg|thumb|A flight of No. 151 Squadron Hurricanes take off from North Weald.]]
At {{nowrap|6:15 a.m.}} on 6 September 1939, a radar fault led to a false alarm that unidentified aircraft were approaching from the east at high altitude over [[West Mersea]], on the [[Essex]] coast.{{sfn|Terraine|1985|p=110}}{{sfn|Yeoman|Freeborn|2009|p=45}} No. 11 Group ordered six [[Hawker Hurricane|Hurricanes]] to be scrambled from [[No. 56 Squadron RAF|56 Squadron]], based at [[North Weald Airfield]] in Essex. The sector controller, [[Group captain|Group Captain]] David Frederick Lucking, sent up the entire unit of 14 aircraft.{{sfn|Blandford|2001|p=16}}{{sfn|Hough|Richards|1990|p=67}} Unbeknown to the rest of the pilots, two Pilot Officers took up a pair of reserve aircraft and followed at a distance.{{sfn|Kaplan|2012|p=51}}

Hurricanes from [[No. 151 Squadron RAF|151 Squadron]] (also from North Weald), and [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfires]] from [[No. 54 Squadron RAF|54]], [[No. 65 Squadron RAF|65]] and [[No. 74 Squadron RAF|74]] Squadrons based at [[Hornchurch Airfield]] scrambled. None of the [[Royal Air Force]] pilots had been in action and few had seen a German aircraft. Communication between the pilots and command centres was poor and there was no procedure for pilots to distinguish between British and ''Luftwaffe'' aircraft. [[Identification friend or foe]] (IFF) sets were still being developed and had not been installed in many RAF aircraft.{{sfn|Cossey|2002|loc=chapter 4}}{{sfn|Hough|Richards|1990|p=67}}

With everyone in the air expecting to see enemy aircraft and no experience of having done so, 'A' Flight of 74 Squadron saw what they believed were German aeroplanes and their commander, [[Adolph Malan|Adolph "Sailor" Malan]], allegedly gave a clear and definite order to engage. Two of the three, Flying Officer Vincent 'Paddy' Byrne and Pilot Officer [[John Freeborn]], opened fire.{{sfn|Bishop|2004|p=108}} Malan later claimed to have given a last minute call of "friendly aircraft – break away!" but if this was true, it was not heard by Byrne and Freeborn.{{sfn|Cossey|2002|loc=chapter 4}} Richard Hough and Denis Richards wrote that further losses were prevented by the 151 Squadron commanding officer, Squadron Leader [[Edward Mortlock Donaldson|Edward Donaldson]], who alerted his pilots that the attacking aircraft were British and gave the order not to retaliate.{{sfn|Hough|Richards|1990|p=67}}

Frank Rose and Pilot Officer Montague Hulton-Harrop were shot down and Hulton-Harrop was killed. Fired upon by John Freeborn, he had been hit in the back of the head and was dead before his Hurricane crashed at Manor Farm, [[Hintlesham]], Suffolk, about {{convert|5|mi|km|abbr=on}} west of [[Ipswich]]. Hulton-Harrop was the first British pilot killed in the war and his Hurricane was the first aircraft shot down by a Spitfire.{{sfn|Kaplan|2012|p=51}} A Spitfire was shot down by British anti-aircraft fire.{{sfn|Terraine|1985|p=110}}

==Aftermath==

===Court martial===

[[File:Supermarine Spitfire Mark Is of No. 610 Squadron based at Biggin Hill, flying in 'vic' formation, 24 July 1940. CH740.jpg|thumb|Supermarine Spitfire Mark Is, 24 July 1940. CH740]]
The [[court martial]] of John Freeborn and Paddy Byrne at the [[Bentley Priory]] headquarters of Fighter Command was held [[in camera]]; in 2010, the papers had still not been released.{{Cn|date=March 2017}} According to author Bill Nasson, it is well known that Freeborn felt that his commanding officer, [[Sailor Malan]], tried to evade responsibility for the attack. Malan testified for the prosecution against his pilots, stating that Freeborn had been irresponsible, impetuous and had not taken proper heed of vital communications.{{sfn|Nasson|2009|p=88}} During the trial, Freeborn's counsel, Sir [[Patrick Hastings]], called Malan a bare-faced liar.{{sfn|Cossey|2002|loc=chapter 4}}

The court exonerated both pilots, ruling that the case was an unfortunate accident.{{Cn|date=March 2017}} In 1990, Hough and Richards wrote, 

{{quote|This tragic shambles, hushed up at the time, was dubbed in the RAF 'the Battle of Barking Creek' – a place several miles from the shooting-down but one which, like [[Wigan Pier]], was a standing joke in the music halls.{{sfn|Hough|Richards|1990|p=67}}}}

In 2003, Patrick Bishop wrote that the incident exposed the inadequacies of RAF radar and identification procedures, leading to them being greatly improved by the crucial period of the [[Battle of Britain]], a view echoed in a 2012 publication by Philip Kaplan.{{sfn|Bishop|2004|pp=109–110}}{{sfn|Kaplan|2012|p=51}}

===Subsequent careers===

Montague Hulton-Harrop is buried with a war grave headstone at St Andrew's Church in [[North Weald]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Commonwealth War Graves Commission entry |url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/2426950 |accessdate=18 August 2010}}</ref> Group Captain Lucking was removed from his post.{{sfn|Holmes|Azaola|1999|p=}} He was an engineering officer who, in the practice of the RAF until the war, served in the General Duties Branch and could be assigned to non-engineering duties.<ref name=LuckingBio>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Biographies/Lucking_DF.htm|title=Air Commodore D F Lucking|website=rafweb.org|access-date=18 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=LuckingIMechE>Institution of Mechanical Engineers, Applications for Membership, 1926</ref><ref name=Lucking3940>Air Force Lists (HMSO), 1939 and 1940</ref> He was returned to engineering duties later that month as OC (Officer Commanding) 32 MU, transferred to the newly formed Technical Branch in 1940 and was promoted to [[air commodore]] in December 1941.<ref name=LuckingAthan>{{cite web|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/modstathan/aboutus/history.cfm|title=RAF St Athan about us|website=raf.mod.uk|access-date=18 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=Lucking4042>Air Force Lists (HMSO), 1940 to 1942</ref> He died in 1970, aged 75.<ref name=Lucking70>Death notice, ''The Times'', 14 March 1970</ref> Frank Rose was killed in action over [[Vitry-en-Artois]], France, on 18 May 1940.<ref>{{citation |title=Commonwealth War Graves Commission entry |url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/2279942 |accessdate = 1 September 2010}}</ref> Malan went on to be one of the most successful Allied fighter pilots of the war, shooting down 27 Luftwaffe aircraft and rising to [[group captain]]. He received the [[Distinguished Service Order]] and [[Medal bar|bar]] and the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]]. On his return to South Africa he worked against the [[apartheid]] regime until his death in 1963.{{sfn|Bishop|2004|p=401}}

Paddy Byrne was shot down and captured over France in 1940. He was detained at ''Stalag Luft III'' alongside his former defence lawyer Roger Bushell. In 1944 he was repatriated, having convinced the Germans and the repatriation board that he was mad. On his return to England he was reinstated into the RAF and given a ground position.{{sfn|Miner Heygood|2010|pp=9–10}} John Freeborn flew more operational hours in the Battle of Britain than any other pilot, remained on operations for the rest of the war and proved to be an outstanding airman. He was awarded the Distinguished Flying Cross and bar and rose to [[Wing Commander (rank)|wing commander]]. Freeborn finally told some of his version of events in a 2002 biography called ''A Tiger's Tale'', before co-authoring a more complete account in ''Tiger Cub''.{{sfn|Cossey|2002|loc=chapter 4}}{{sfn|Yeoman|Freeborn|2009|loc=chapter 3}} In 2009, Freeborn told an interviewer of his regret about Hulton-Harrop's death, saying, "I think about him nearly every day. I always have done... I've had a good life, and he should have had a good life too".<ref>{{cite news |title=Watch: Spitfire pilot John Freeborn's story |publisher=BBC |date=3 September 2009 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/theoneshow/onepassions/2009/09/watch-spitfire-pilot-john-free.html |accessdate=18 August 2010}}</ref> Freeborn was twice married, first in 1941 to Rita Fielder, who died in 1979 and then Peta in 1983, who died in 2001. Freeborn died on 28 August 2010 and was survived by a daughter from his first marriage.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wing Commander John Freeborn |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=14 September 2010 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/military-obituaries/air-force-obituaries/8002880/Wing-Commander-John-Freeborn.html |accessdate=14 September 2010 |location=London}}</ref>

