===In 2017=== The third annual Day to Praise took place on 2 May 2017 and the central event was held in [[Jerusalem]].<ref name="bfpmay2017">{{cite web|url=http://www.bridgesforpeace.com/2017/05/day-praise-jews-christians-unite-praise-god-miracle-israel-2/|title=Day to Praise – Jews, Christians Unite to Praise God for the Miracle of Israel|first=Ilse|last=Posselt|publisher=Bridges for Peace|date=5 May 2017|access-date=6 May 2017}}</ref> As per tradition, the Jewish and Christian attendees celebrated by reciting the Psalms 113–118 reportedly joined by hundreds more from around the world. Event co-founder, David Nekrutman, stated that one of the main themes at this year's event was seeing "the importance of looking at one another and walking together" within the Psalms themselves. This year's event also marked the [[golden jubilee]] of the reunification of Jerusalem.<ref name="bfpmay2017" /> A week before celebrations began, a Day to Praise Hallel service was held in Germany by a group of 125 Christians. It was also reported that a few days later, the [[synagogue]] in [[Youngstown, Ohio]] invited Christians to join them for a Hallel service.<ref name="bfpmay2017" />
===In 2018=== [[File:Day to Praise 2018 - 6.jpg|thumb|260px|Attendees at the 4th annual Day to Praise Israel Independence Day event, 18 April 2018]] The fourth annual Day to Praise took place on 19 April 2018. The central event was held on the eve of April 18 and began with a [[Yom Hazikaron|Memorial Day]] ceremony for Israel's fallen soldiers. Jews and Christians joined together in an event which "took them from the depths of sadness over Israel’s losses in wars for survival, to the heights of joy on Israel’s 70th anniversary".<ref name="binapril2018">{{cite web|url=https://www.breakingisraelnews.com/106432/jews-and-christians-join-together-in-day-of-praise-for-israels-70th/|title=Jews and Christians Join Together in Day of Praise for Israel's 70th|first=Adam|last=Eliyahu Berkowitz|publisher=Breaking Israel News|date=23 April 2018|access-date=24 April 2018}}</ref> This year's central event was held at the [[John Hagee]] Center for Jewish Heritage at the [[Netanya Academic College]] where reportedly around 350 Jews and Christians were in attendance. As with every Day to Praise event, attendees recited the Psalms of Praise. Associate director of CJCUC, Rabbi Pesach Wolicki, stated that Christians praising God and praying for Israel is "an essential piece of the prophetic puzzle" and that without them the prophecies about Israel's future ''geula'' (redemption) would not be complete.<ref name="binapril2018" />
