{{Infobox event | title = First Interstate Tower fire | image = First Interstate Tower fire.png | caption = The First Interstate Tower, with several floors burning. | date = {{Start date|1988|5|4}} | venue = First Interstate Tower | location = [[Los Angeles, California]], [[United States]] | coordinates = {{Coord|34|2|57.2|N|118|15|25.7|W|display=title, inline}} | type = [[Fire]] | cause =Overloaded electrical system | reported deaths = 1 | reported injuries = 40 | reported missing = | reported property damage = | arrests = | suspects = | accused = | convicted = | charges = | verdict = | convictions = | sentence = }} The '''First Interstate Tower fire''' was a [[Skyscraper fire|high-rise fire]] that occurred on May 4, 1988, at the First Interstate Tower (now [[Aon Center (Los Angeles)|Aon Center]]) in [[Los Angeles, California]]. The fire destroyed five floors of the building, injured 40 people, and caused the death of a maintenance worker, when the elevator the worker was riding opened onto the burning 12th floor.<ref name="TechReport">{{cite web|url=http://www.lafire.com/famous_fires/880504_1stInterstateFire/FEMA-TecReport/FEMA-report.htm|title=Technical Report, Interstate Bank Building Fire|publisher=[[United States Fire Administration]]|accessdate=2009-11-21|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.lafire.com%2Ffamous_fires%2F880504_1stInterstateFire%2FFEMA-TecReport%2FFEMA-report.htm&date=2010-07-13 |archivedate=2010-07-13 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-08-27/local/me-939_1_fire-door|last=Becklund|first=Laurie|title=Open Fire Door Blamed in First Interstate Death|publisher=The L.A. Times|date=1988-08-27|accessdate=2017-10-19}}</ref>
==Causes and results== The fire's origin has been attributed to overloading of the building's electrical system by reactive [[distortion]] of lighting circuit currents.<ref name=glasband1>{{cite web|last=Glasband|first=Eric|title="Lifting" the Grounding Enigma|url=http://www.equitech.com/articles/enigma.html|publisher=MIX Magazine|accessdate=2012-12-13|date=November 1994}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=January 2017}}
The fire was so severe because the building was not equipped with a [[Fire sprinkler system|sprinkler system]], which was not required for office towers at the time construction was completed in 1973. A sprinkler system was 90% installed at the time of the fire, but the system was inoperative, awaiting the installation of water flow alarms.<ref name="TechReport" /> The fire was eventually contained at 2:19 AM, and caused $50 million in damages.
According to the [https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.lafire.com%2Ffamous_fires%2F880504_1stInterstateFire%2FFEMA-TecReport%2FFEMA-report.htm&date=2010-07-13 FEMA fire incident report] on the subject, unusually good application of [[fireproofing]] on support members was a significant mitigating factor. The efficacy of the fireproofing was documented both by FEMA and [http://view.officeapps.live.com/op/view.aspx?src=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.firestop.org%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2FIFC_Presentation_Jan-05_-_2_HOUR.ppt IFC]. Fireproofing of structural steel in the US is tested to [http://www.astm.org/Standards/E119.htm ASTM E119 Standard Test Methods for Fire Tests of Building Construction and Materials].
Repair work took four months. Because of the fire, Los Angeles building codes were changed, requiring all high-rises to be equipped with fire sprinklers. This modified a 1974 ordinance that only required new buildings to contain fire sprinkler systems, [[Grandfather clause|grandfathering]] older buildings.
==Cultural references== The fire was dramatized in the 1991 [[telefilm]], ''Fire: Trapped on the 37th Floor'', starring [[Lee Majors]], [[Lisa Hartman Black]] and [[Peter Scolari]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-10-25/local/me-4052_1_interstate-fire|last=Jones|first=Charisse|title=Adding Film to the Fire : Re-Enacted for TV, First Interstate Blaze Is Relived by Survivors|publisher=The L.A. Times|date=1990-10-25|accessdate=2017-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/1991/02/15/fire-trapped-37th-floor/|last=Tucker|first=Ken|title=Review: Fire! Trapped on the 37th Floor|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|date=1991-02-15|accessdate=2017-10-19}}</ref>
