{{Multiple image|image1=Essen-Ruhr Stadttheater.jpg|caption1=Grillo-Theater, c. 1910|width1=247|image2=Essen Grillo Theater Front 1 2005.jpg|caption2=Grillo-Theater, 2005}}
'''Grillo-Theater ''' is a theatre in [[Essen]], Germany. Named after the industrialist [[Friedrich Grillo]], who made the building possible, it opened on 16 September 1892 with [[Gotthold Ephraim Lessing|Lessing]]'s drama ''[[Minna von Barnhelm]]''.

The building was badly damaged in World War II; it was restored with a much simpler façade and re-opened in 1950 with Wagner's opera ''[[Die Meistersinger von Nürnberg]]''. Notable directors included [[Erwin Piscator]], [[Jean-Louis Barrault]], [[:de:Heinz Dietrich Kenter|Heinz Dietrich Kenter]], [[:de:Hansgünter Heyme|Hansgünter Heyme]]. [[Caspar Neher]] became head of design in 1927 and designed here eight operas and 11 plays.

In 1988, the role of the Grillo-Theater as Essen's major stage venue was taken by the newly constructed [[Aalto Theatre]] which also opened with ''Die Meistersinger''. Following a major reconstruction by the architect [[:de:Werner Ruhau|Werner Ruhau]] and a reduction of the auditorium from 670 to 400 seats, the Grillo-Theater became a flexible smaller venue; it re-opened in September 1990 with Shakespeare's ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream]]''.
[[File:Friedrich_Grillo_am_Grillo-Theater.jpg|thumb|x150px|Commemorative plaque for [[Friedrich Grillo]] on the south side of the theatre]]
